</noscript></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><font class="h1font"> DC....Overpowered?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/vs/main/mpage.php?member=1805'>Kenneth "Ken B" Bradford</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/vs/main/mpage.php?member=1805&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 2, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> With the new DC set coming out, there have been a lot of cries of &quot;power escalation!&quot; and &quot;Broken!&quot;  Unfortunately, whenever an expansion for a CCG comes out, inevitably these cries are always heard (except for Decipher games, where it&#39;s an alternating &quot;This card is useless!&quot; and &quot;This card is broken!&quot;)  In fact, from what I&#39;ve read the general consensus is that the new DC set blows the old Marvel guys right out of the water, obsoleting them entirely.<br><br>Hogwash, I thought.<br><br>Could it be true?  I mean, other companies have done it before, even Upper Deck&#39;s own <b>Yu-Gi-Oh</b> suffers from this power escalation syndrome, where &quot;power cards&quot; from a year ago can be had for a buck or two today.  Why would <b>VS</b> be any different from one of these past offenders?<br><br><br><b><u>Upper Deck Takes This Game Very Seriously</u></b><br><br>It&#39;s a pretty commonly known fact that VS was actually given some intense playtesting prior to its release.  In fact, when Upper Deck submitted its first rev to the players, these players came back and told them--&quot;This game sucks.&quot;<br><br>Now, unlike Decipher who feels like criticism from their players is misinformed at best and meaningless in general, Upper Deck took this criticism to heart and went back to the drawing board, delaying the release of the game by several months.  To me, this was what first got my attention about VS--word on the &#39;net was that Upper Deck really was trying to make the game the best they possibly could.<br><br>The game, of course, benefitted from this delay and subsequent retooling and went on to sell bajillions of cards after the release of <b>Origins</b>.  And if Upper Deck was willing to be so careful with the yet unproven game, just how careful do you think they&#39;ll be with a PROVEN CASH COW?  I&#39;ll put my money on the fact that they&#39;re watching this one with extreme care.<br><br>After all, currently the game is attracting in Magic players, Heroclix fans, Raw Dealers, LOTR players, you name it.  Plus, it&#39;s a natural graduation point for kiddies to leap from Yu-Gi-Oh to VS.  Wizards and Decipher have both been trying to work on this sort of one-two punch for years now, and just like that, Upper Deck has it.<br><br>And this property is HOT, friends.  With interest in comic book characters and movies at an all time high (look no further than Spider-Man 2&#39;s $40.5 Million grossing <i>Wednesday</i>), look for this property to remain hot--that is, if Halle Berry&#39;s Catwoman movie doesn&#39;t kill the whole craze dead on impact.<br><br>Honestly, I&#39;ve had kids ask me to trade for my Origins <b>Spider-Man</b> just because he&#39;s &quot;cool&quot; right now (even though his card is balls, though that&#39;s an article for another day).<br><br><br><b><u>Are These Cards <i>Really</i> Broken?</u></b><br><br>Once you get past the assumption that Upper Deck is just ramping up the power on us, you start looking at specific card examples and really start to question their relative &quot;brokenness&quot;.  Are they really better than their Marvel counterparts?  Or like much of the rest of the game, are there some subtle things here and there that may make you re-evaluate those assumptions?<br><br>After all, most of us after just a few hands of this game proclaimed, &quot;No Game Can Make It Past Turn Seven.&quot;  And we&#39;ve seen <i>that</i> proven false.  Now we&#39;re making assumptions without even playing with the cards yet!<br><br>So let&#39;s take a look at a few of the cards that are being claimed to be &quot;superior&quot;, and see if these claims hold up.<br><br><br />
<UL><LI><P><b>Have a Blast!</b>:  Most are saying that this little gem is going to 100% replace <b>Kaboom!</b> and <b>Relocation</b> in  many decks.  I&#39;d say that this claim is right...sort of.  You see, I&#39;m pretty sure that Upper Deck never intended for Locations to be as dominant as they are currently.  Every deck you see is in some way powered by locations:  New Brotherhood, Big Brotherhood, Fantastic Four ARB, Doom Bomb w/ Doomstadt and Latveria...on and on and on.</P><P>I&#39;d say that, like most companies after a first set (Star Wars had some &quot;dogs&quot; in that Premiere set, as I remember), they are simply trying to introduce a card as it maybe should&#39;ve been from the start.  Plus, this doesn&#39;t mean that all the utility of <b>Relocation</b> or <b>Kaboom</b> are gone;  I think they probably designed <b>Ka-Boom</b> to benefit decks who could work on fewer resources, <i>not</i> become one of our only defenses against location abuse.</P><P>And take another hard look at <b>Relocation</b> before you toss it away;  remember, in <b>Have a Blast&#39;s</b> case, your opponent actually replaces the destroyed card with another face-down one.  Note this could be a <b>Savage Beatdown</b> or <b>Flying Kick</b> or heck, even <i>another copy of the card you nuked.</i>  With <b>Relocation</b>, you essentially give them nothing in return, and you can even get utility out of some of the locations you steal (<b>Avalon Space Station</b>, I&#39;m looking right at you.)</P><P>Now sure, <b>Have a Blast</b> deals with Ongoing Plot Twists....but I haven&#39;t seen many of those outside of Brotherhood decks.  And I&#39;m NOT going to weep if those guys take a hit, believe me.</P><br />
<LI><P><b>Fizzle!</b>:  This card has gotten a lot of attention recently, and for good reason--VS has gotten its first near all-purpose &quot;Counterspell&quot;.  Sure, we had <b>Not So Fast</b> in the beginning, but NOW we&#39;re talking some serious countering power!</P><P>But you know what?  Only <b>Gotham Knights</b> get to use it.  Are they a good faction?  Yeah, I&#39;d say they&#39;re decent.  So is <b>Fizzle</b> broken, then?  I&#39;d argue instead that much like <b>Sabretooth, Feral Rage</b> is the &quot;clutch&quot; card for Brotherhood (let&#39;s face it--NBH *and* BBH would be lost without him), <b>Fizzle</b> is the card that will be the <i>reason</i> that Gotham Knights are competitive.  Without a card of that magnitude, they&#39;d likely be too weak to play!</P><P>Honestly, look at the faction.  I see some good stuff...but a lot of confusion in the faction as well.  Part of it seems to want to fight...part of it seems to want to control...part of it seems to want to discard its own cards, and others encourage you to have lots of cards in hand.  This sort of confusion reminds me of another team in the VS set--<b>X-Men</b>.  X-Men just sort of have a little of everything, and their signature card <b>Children of the Atom</b> really doesn&#39;t push them as far forward as the cards of others.</P><P>So for all other decks, it&#39;s still <b>Not So Fast</b> as usual, which STILL hits the majority of stuff in the early to mid-game you&#39;re going to want it to (<b>Overload, Burn Rubber, Flying Kick</b>...).  And last but not least, <b>Not So Fast</b> lets you discard any old card that isn&#39;t proving useful at the moment, while <b>Fizzle</b> requires you to pitch a Gotham Knights character.  This is probably the key reason the card got toned down so much--originally <b>Fizzle</b> was called Bat-Computer and would allow you to pitch any two cards or one Gotham Knights character to use it.  Had it stayed like that....broken.  As it is, perfectly balanced within the confines laid out for us.</P><br />
<LI><P><b>Bat-Signal:</b>  This one I&#39;ve also heard quite a bit:  &quot;<b>Bat-Signal</b> is better than <b>Signal Flare</b>!&quot;  And on the surface this would appear to be true.  After all, you don&#39;t even have to discard a character to use it!</P><P>However, I think most people are discounting the utility of an unexhausted character.  Once a character exhausts for a plot twist like <b>Bat-Signal</b>, they can&#39;t do anything else.  They can&#39;t attack, can&#39;t reinforce, can&#39;t exhaust to use their own abilities....so there is some opportunity cost involved in exhausting a character like this.  This is lessened when you are able to pitch a character from hand because obviously you couldn&#39;t or didn&#39;t want to pay the cost for the character at that time.  So I&#39;d say that, at least on that level, they&#39;re pretty even--it just depends on how you view the associated cost with which one you value more.</P><P>Plus, the reduced cost of <b>Bat-Signal</b> is actually a liability with very little benefit.  Sure it only costs 1, but how many times have you Signal Flared for a 1 or 2 drop?  That is a HUGE waste, and I doubt the 1-cost will be a factor for Gotham Knights in that regard.  However, it will be a factor in the card <b>Not So Fast</b>, which can nail <b>Bat-Signal</b> but not <b>Signal Flare.</b></P><P>You see?  These Upper Deck guys <i>are</i> paying attention!  And this attention to detail has given me even more confidence in this game going the distance and continuing to be a big success.</P><LI><P><b>Ra&#39;s Al Ghul:</b>  Some attention has been paid to Ra&#39;s apparent mastery of Locations and how this affects many of the current decks that are running around today.  But did they design this faction just to be the answer to that, or is that damage incidental?</P><P>First, I&#39;m pretty sure that UD never intended for Brotherhood to be <i>this</i> dominant.  There were glimmers of hope when the first big tourney results came in and decks other than Brotherhood took the top spot.  That optimism was short-lived, however, as Brotherhood has been a dominating factor in every top 8 since, and has won several major events in either its New Brotherhood or Big Brotherhood forms.  So if a faction is released that helps with this problem, I&#39;m all for it--there should be at least some risk in playing any deck, and we finally have a few answers to the speed and location abuse of the Brotherhood.</P><P>Plus, it&#39;s not like they chose this arbitrary representation of the <b>League Of Assassin&#39;s</b> focus.  Ra&#39;s is an eco-terrorist, and the only thing we really have to represent that are Location cards.  This theme fits him perfectly, as he can either sabotage or overtake any location he wants to!  So I think it&#39;s a combination of an appropriate power that just happens to nerf an existing strategy a little--no harm there, you ask me.</P><br />
<LI><P><b>Great Character Cards:</b>  The first time you read over some of the abilities of some of the new characters, it might make your head spin.  Take control of characters?  KO a stunned character?  Kill resources at will?  As Joe Schmo might say, &quot;WHAT IS GOING ON?!&quot;</P><br />
<P>But look closer--these DC guys can&#39;t hold their own as well in a fight as their Marvel counterparts.  Sure, there are a few scrappers--Batman&#39;s 5-drop is a combat machine, but what would you expect?--however, most of the stats you actually see on these cards are lower or have significant drawbacks.</P><P>Look at <b>Lady Shiva</b> from the LoA, for example.  She&#39;s a 7-drop who can exhaust to KO target character.  The first time you read that, you&#39;re like &quot;Whoa!  WTF?!&quot;  But you have to take into account that she&#39;s only 13/13--<b>Mr. Fantastic</b> was previously the smallest 7-drop at 14/14, and no one considered him a combat machine!  And since her ability can only be used during the owner&#39;s combat phase, she has to make it there un-stunned in order to do her dirty work.  If your opponent has initiative, that&#39;s probably not going to happen, as all guns will be blazing for her!</P><br />
<P>Plus, it comes back to utility cost--when I play a 7-drop, I expect it to crack some heads and win me the game.  If Shiva exhausts to do her thing, she can&#39;t swing at your opponent--meaning she actually does no damage!  Considering many games end at 7, she might get dropped only for her controller to lose the game that very turn!</P><P>And as far as undercosted combat beasts are concerned, it&#39;s no contest.  There&#39;s not a single 4-drop on the DC side that holds a candle to Feral Sabretooth.  Even without his New Brotherhood or Lost City pumps, the man stuns anything and can <i>natrually</i> trade with some 6-drops--and many of those 6 drops are DC!  Same for <b>Thing, Heavy Hitter</b>--heck, there&#39;s a 6-drop who&#39;s 11/11 and can&#39;t even be Singal Flared for in the DC set--Thing would just <b>Clobberin&#39; Time</b> the Fool and be done with it!</P><P>So DC = sneaky.  But Marvel = Bash Your Teeth In.  You&#39;ve been warned.</P><br />
<LI><P><b>Mega-blast:</b>  I&#39;ve saved this one for last just because I think it&#39;s the one that deserves the most evalutation.  Already many are saying that it obsoletes both <b>Flying Kick</b> and to some degree the mighty <b>Savage Beatdown.</b></P><P>I hope you guys are kidding.</P><P>I&#39;m not saying <b>Mega-blast</b> isn&#39;t good--in fact, it&#39;s a GREAT card that&#39;s going to find it&#39;s way into lots of decks.  But as far as &quot;straight-up better&quot;?  For one, <b>Flying Kick</b> grants Flight.  I hope we&#39;ve all played enough VS to know that most of the time Flight is far more valuable than Range, because Flight lets you get at those back-row chumps like Puppet Master who are trying to escape your wrath.  And <b>Savage Beatdown</b> still gives you +5...which can certainly mean the difference in trading with someone 2 or 3 drops higher than you or not, the greatest strength that Beatdown already has.  Just look at some character matchups and I think you&#39;ll see that the +1 pump can make a LOT of difference in trading stuns with a bigger character.</P>Not to mention that the character must be in the support row to have this played on them.  Sure, they can move out during the formation step, but at least briefly they&#39;ve got to be in the support row.  This means that someone like <b>Dazzler</b> (or worse, the f&#39;n <b>Green Goblin</b>, remember him?) have a chance to deal with the attacker before he ever even gets to swing.</P><P>Oh, and the threshold cost on Mega-Blast?  <b>Not So Fast</b>, bub.  That&#39;s all I&#39;m sayin&#39;....</P></UL><br><br><br>So there are my thoughts thus far at least on the new DC set.  I hope I&#39;m right and that the new cards don&#39;t just dominate the scene, because that always has negative repurcussions down the road--just ask any Star Wars CCG player!  Hopefully, this has given you something to think about before you cast your Marvel cards aside in disgust.<br><br>I hope you have a great holiday weekend--in fact, Have a Blast!<br><br><i>*GROAN*</i><br><br>Thanks for reading!<br><br><br>Ken Bradford<br>Decktech Wastelands Admin<br><br> <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/vs/articles/articles.php?id=5698&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/vs/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/vs/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></div></div>


